data.content:
This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change.

**What happened:** In C# 14, new built-in `Span<T>` / `ReadOnlySpan<T>` conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` (a span-based method) instead of `Enumerable.Contains`. `MemoryExtensions.Contains` is **not representable in an expression tree**, so it throws at runtime when the expression is compiled/interpreted.

**Fix:** Force the compiler to pick `Enumerable.Contains` by casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option A: cast inside the expression
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option B: use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option C: call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Any of these disambiguate overload resolution so the expression tree references the supported `Enumerable.Contains` method.
